The slast language purpose is to write code  without explicit use of the QAST API.
But plenty of code
is written using that very API. We don't want to manually convert that code to slast.
So we design the SynTrans language that does syntaxical transforms.
Here it is used
to transform parts of a program using the QAST API into AST phasers.
So as far as QAST is concerned, this language is intended to compile a unique program
to generate the transformer program that does get rid of QAST API call.
But we eventually intend to use SynTrans in a syntax aware editor.

A sequence of rules defines the transforms.


One transform is constituted of a parse tree pattern and its transformation.

The transform will walk the parse tree and search patterns that apply,

A parse tree pattern is represented by the string that lead to the parse tree
with the exception of holes.
To support patterns,  we just need to extend the grammar of the language in which the program is written.

The transformed program will not be indented properly.
We need to extend SynTrans to support intelligent indentation including vertical alignement
of similar substructures in consecutive lines. 


